Scatterplot Transformation

qplot(data=diamonds,x=carat,y=price)+scale_y_log10()+geom_point()

Create a new function to transform the carat variable

cuberoot_trans = function() trans_new('cuberoot', transform = function(x) x^(1/3),
                                      inverse = function(x) x^3)

Use the cuberoot_trans function

ggplot(aes(carat, price), data = diamonds) + 
  geom_point() + 
  scale_x_continuous(trans = cuberoot_trans(), limits = c(0.2, 3),
                     breaks = c(0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 3)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(trans = log10_trans(), limits = c(350, 15000),
                     breaks = c(350, 1000, 5000, 10000, 15000)) +
  ggtitle('Price (log10) by Cube-Root of Carat')

Linear Models in R

Response: We use linear regression here, since the output variable, Price, is of continuous values, and is affected by more than one input variable.

Building the Linear Model

Notes: We choose are ouput as log(price) , since we are predicting diamonds prices, and we select our input/explanatory variable as cube-root of carat, since it has previously shown a linear relation with price.

m1 <- lm(I(log(price)) ~ I(carat^(1/3)), data = diamonds)
m2 <- update(m1, ~ . + carat)
m3 <- update(m2, ~ . + cut)
m4 <- update(m3, ~ . + color)
m5 <- update(m4, ~ . + clarity)
mtable(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, sdigits=3)

Notice how adding cut to our model does not help explain much of the variance in the price of diamonds. This fits with out exploration earlier.

Problems with model

Response:
1) data set is old, therefore current inflation not considered. 2) diamond prices have changed due to different new factors within carat itself, therefore the old data might not support predictions for modern-day prices.

diamondsBig <- read.csv('diamondsbig.csv')
diamondsBig$logprice=log(diamondsBig$price)
m1 <- lm(I(logprice) ~ I(carat^(1/3)),
         data=diamondsBig[diamondsBig$price<10000 & diamondsBig$cert=="GIA",])
m2 <- update(m1, ~ . + carat)
m3 <- update(m2, ~ . + cut)
m4 <- update(m3, ~ . + color)
m5 <- update(m4, ~ . + clarity)
mtable(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, sdigits=3)

Predictions

We try an example: Example Diamond from BlueNile: Round 1.00 Very Good I VS1 $5,601

library(memisc)
thisDiamond = data.frame(carat = 1.00, cut = "V.Good",
                         color = "I", clarity="VS1")
modelEstimate = predict(m5, newdata = thisDiamond,
                        interval="prediction", level = .95)
exp(modelEstimate)
##        fit     lwr      upr
## 1 5040.436 3730.34 6810.638

Final Thoughts

Notes: The model predicts a price slightly higher than the actual value but well within the expected price.

Actual Price: 5000 Predicted Price: 5040

This is within the 95% confidence interval, we used to predict the price. ***
